      Types of Mental disorders

Anxiety disorders and depression are most common

Anxiety disorders affect 18.1% of the U.S population

Only 36.9% of people suffering from Anxiety receive treatment

People with Anxiety are 5 time more likely to go to the doctor and 6 times more likely to be
hospitalized for psychiatric disorders than those who do not suffer from anxiety

It's not uncommon for people with anxiety to also suffer from depression

The most commonly diagnosed form of depression is Major Depressive Disorder

in 2015 around 16.1 million adults aged 18 or older in the U.S have experienced at least 1 major depressive  episode in the past year.

MDD is characterized by five of the diagnostic symptoms of which at least one of the symptoms must be overwhelming feeling of sadness or a loss of interest and pleasure in most usual activities

other symptoms of MDD include decrease or increase in appetite, insomnia or hypersomnia, psycho motor agitation or retardation, constant fatigue, feeling of worthlessness or excessive and inappropriate guilt, recurrent thoughts of death and suicidal ideation, cognitive difficulties, ect.

Persistent depressive disorder or PDD is another form of depression

PDD usually continues for at least 2 years

PDD affects approx. 1.5% of the U.S population age 18 and older


bipolar disorder is a brain disorder that causes unusual shifts in a person's mood and ability to function

The mood episodes persist from days to weeks or longer, and can be dramatic with periods of being overly high and/or irritable to periods of persistent sadness and hopelessness


People with eating disorders develop habits that can cause great deal of harm

eating disorders may fast or severely restrict their calories, exercise for hours on end each day, or take other actions to prevent any weight gain.

people with eating disorders are often underweight they have an intense fear of becoming overweight

Another category of eating disorders is EDNOS (Eating Disorders Not Otherwise Specified)

Most of the eating disorders included in EDNOS are similar to anorexia or bulimia

Most people with eating disorders are suffering from other mental disorders


Social Anxiety Disorder (SAD) affects 15 million adults, 6.8% of the U.S population

SAD is equally as common in both men and women

SAD typically begins at age 13

According to a ADAA survey in 2007, 36% of people reported having symptoms for 10 or more years


      Treatment

The Vast majority of people with most mental disorders can be treated, some respond to treatment after a few weeks or months

Treatment may be complicated if they have more than one mental disorder

Treatment for anxiety has to be specific to the person getting the treatment

Getting professional help is the best way to help treat mental disorders

If therapy is too much you can seek support and therapy groups in your community

Some therapy providers offer a sliding scale. A sliding scale is what some providers use to lower the cost based on your income
